#
# WHAT IS lipgloss AND WHY IS IT THE 44TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# lipgloss (https://github.com/charmbracelet/lipgloss, 11353+
# stars) is **Charm's "Style definitions for nice terminal
# layouts"** — a Go library that brings CSS-LIKE styling
# semantics to terminal output.  Created by the Charm team
# (Christian Rocha, Maas Lalani, Bashbunni, Bryanl, et al.) in
# 2021 as the styling companion to bubbletea.  Where bubbletea
# handles the Elm Architecture for TUI logic, lipgloss handles
# the VISUAL APPEARANCE of the terminal output.
#
# lipgloss's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. CSS-LIKE STYLING DSL — lipgloss styles use a method-chained
#      builder API mirroring CSS properties:
#
#          var style = lipgloss.NewStyle().
#              Foreground(lipgloss.Color("#FAFAFA")).
#              Background(lipgloss.Color("#7D56F4")).
#              Padding(2, 4, 2, 4).      // top right bottom left
#              MarginLeft(2).
#              Border(lipgloss.RoundedBorder()).
#              BorderForeground(lipgloss.Color("63")).
#              Width(40).
#              Align(lipgloss.Center).
#              Bold(true)
#          output := style.Render("Hello, World!")
#
#      Compare:
#         * fatih/color R527:    color attributes only (no padding/
#                                  border/width)
#         * termcolor R546:      ColorSpec builder for color only
#         * owo-colors R526:     trait extension methods (text +
#                                  color only)
#         * blessed-contrib R540: inline style tags ({bold}word{/bold})
#      lipgloss is the FIRST documented terminal library with FULL
#      CSS-LIKE BOX-MODEL semantics (margin + padding + border +
#      width + height + alignment).
#
#   2. RUNE-AWARE LAYOUT — lipgloss's `Width()` and `Height()`
#      methods compute layout based on terminal-cell widths (not
#      byte counts), correctly handling:
#         - CJK double-width characters (中文 → 4 cells)
#         - Emoji sequences (👨‍💻 → 2 cells)
#         - Zero-width joiners and combining diacritics
#         - ANSI escape sequences (excluded from width)
#      Compare fatih/color R527 (no layout, no width awareness)
#      and termcolor R546 (color only).  FIRST documented Go
#      terminal library with Unicode-grapheme-cluster-aware layout.
#
#   3. JOIN PRIMITIVES — lipgloss provides `JoinHorizontal()` and
#      `JoinVertical()` primitives for composing multiple styled
#      blocks:
#
#          left  := style1.Render("Left pane content")
#          right := style2.Render("Right pane content")
#          row   := lipgloss.JoinHorizontal(
#              lipgloss.Top, left, right)
#          page  := lipgloss.JoinVertical(
#              lipgloss.Left, header, row, footer)
#
#      Compare:
#         * bubbletea R531: string concatenation in View() —
#                            BUT bubbletea CALLS lipgloss's
#                            JoinHorizontal/JoinVertical for
#                            multi-pane layouts.
#         * tview R535:      Flex/Grid container nesting
#         * ratatui R530:    Constraint-based layout
#      FIRST documented Go terminal library with explicit
#      JoinHorizontal/JoinVertical compositional primitives.
#
#   4. INHERITS + COPY MECHANISM FOR STYLE COMPOSITION — lipgloss
#      styles support `.Inherit(parent)` which copies UNSET
#      properties from parent style, allowing style hierarchies:
#
#          var baseStyle = lipgloss.NewStyle().
#              BorderStyle(lipgloss.RoundedBorder()).
#              Padding(1, 2)
#
#          var headerStyle = baseStyle.Copy().
#              Foreground(lipgloss.Color("#FAFAFA")).
#              Background(lipgloss.Color("#7D56F4"))
#
#          var errorStyle = baseStyle.Copy().
#              Foreground(lipgloss.Color("#FF0000"))
#
#      `.Inherit(parent)` (different from `.Copy()`) is more
#      similar to CSS cascading — parent values flow down for
#      unset properties.  Compare:
#         * fatih/color:  no inheritance
#         * termcolor:    no inheritance
#         * owo-colors:   chained method calls (no separation)
#      FIRST documented Go terminal library with CSS-like style
#      inheritance / copy.
#
#   5. ADAPTIVE COLOR (LIGHT/DARK MODE) — lipgloss's `AdaptiveColor`
#      type holds TWO color values:
#
#          var primary = lipgloss.AdaptiveColor{
#              Light: "#1A1A1A",  // for light terminals
#              Dark:  "#FAFAFA",  // for dark terminals
#          }
#
#      lipgloss auto-detects the terminal's background via OSC 11
#      (Operating System Command 11 — query background color) on
#      startup and selects the appropriate color variant.  Compare
#      every other documented terminal-color library — none detect
#      light/dark terminal mode.  FIRST documented terminal-color
#      library with adaptive light/dark color selection.
#
# lipgloss's relationship to other documented Go CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like bubbletea R531    — Charmbracelet ecosystem (3rd Charm
#                                library documented)
#   * Like huh R543           — Charmbracelet ecosystem
#   * Like fatih/color R527   — terminal coloring (same axis,
#                                different generation)
#   * Like blessed-contrib R540 — extends another base library
#                                  (lipgloss extends bubbletea)
#   * Unlike all of the above — CSS-LIKE BOX-MODEL + RUNE-AWARE
#                                LAYOUT + JOIN COMPOSITION +
#                                STYLE INHERITANCE + ADAPTIVE
#                                LIGHT/DARK
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    ratatui's `Style` + `Block` API (ratatui
#                     bundles styling INTO the widget tree;
#                     lipgloss is style-only, applied to strings)
#         * TS-Node: ink's `<Text color="red" backgroundColor=
#                     "#000" bold>` (React-attribute styling,
#                     similar CSS-ish API but JSX-attribute-based
#                     rather than method-chain-based)
#     lipgloss is unique in having BOTH method-chain CSS-builder
#     AND inheritance semantics applied to PLAIN STRINGS rather
#     than widgets/components.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE termdbms CLI — Go-Stdlib `flag` + bubbletea + lipgloss
#
# termdbms's argv parser is Go stdlib `flag`:
#
#     var debug, help, ascii bool
#     var path, databaseType, theme string
#
#     flag.StringVar(&databaseType, "d", "sqlite",
#         "Specifies the SQL driver to use.")
#     flag.StringVar(&path, "p", "", "Path to database file.")
#     flag.StringVar(&theme, "t", "default",
#         "sets the color theme of the app.")
#     flag.BoolVar(&help, "h", false, "Prints the help message.")
#     flag.BoolVar(&ascii, "a", false,
#         "Render with minimal styling to remove ANSI sequences.")
#     flag.Parse()
#
# Five flags total.  Theme handling routes to one of:
#   - default (lipgloss default colors)
#   - solarized (Solarized Dark theme)
#   - dracula (Dracula theme)
#   - catppuccin (Catppuccin Mocha theme)
# When `-a` is given, all lipgloss styles render as plain text
# (color/background/border stripped).
#
# Distinct from every other documented Go CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. CSS-LIKE BOX-MODEL STYLING — Every other documented Go
#      terminal library handles either colors only (fatih/color
#      R527) or full TUI widgets (bubbletea/tview/termui).  lipgloss
#      occupies the MIDDLE GROUND: CSS-like styling applied to
#      plain strings, no widget tree, no event loop.  FIRST
#      documented Go library with CSS-like box-model styling
#      applied to strings.
#
#   2. RUNE-AWARE LAYOUT — Every other documented Go terminal
#      library uses byte counts or doesn't compute layout.
#      lipgloss explicitly handles Unicode grapheme clusters,
#      CJK double-width, emoji ZWJ sequences.  FIRST documented
#      Go terminal library with grapheme-cluster-aware width
#      calculation for layout.
#
#   3. JOIN PRIMITIVES — Every other documented Go terminal
#      library uses container nesting (tview/termui) or string
#      concatenation (bubbletea/fatih).  lipgloss has explicit
#      JoinHorizontal/JoinVertical primitives that handle
#      alignment, gap, and per-element styling.  FIRST documented
#      Go terminal library with first-class join primitives.
#
#   4. STYLE INHERITANCE — Every other documented Go terminal
#      library has no inheritance / copy semantics.  lipgloss's
#      `.Inherit(parent)` and `.Copy()` enable CSS-style cascading
#      where child styles override only specific properties.
#      FIRST documented Go terminal library with style inheritance.
#
#   5. ADAPTIVE LIGHT/DARK COLOR — Every other documented Go
#      terminal library renders fixed colors regardless of terminal
#      background.  lipgloss's AdaptiveColor type holds two values
#      (Light/Dark) and selects based on OSC 11 query response.
#      FIRST documented Go terminal library with adaptive
#      light/dark mode color selection.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/mathaou/termdbms/blob/master/main.go
# `flag.StringVar` and `flag.BoolVar` calls.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '-h[print the help message]' \
    '-d+[SQL driver to use (default sqlite)]:driver:(sqlite mysql)' \
    '-p+[path to the database file]:file:_files -g "*.(db|sqlite|sqlite3)"' \
    '-t+[color theme]:theme:(default solarized dracula catppuccin)' \
    '-a[render with minimal styling (ASCII-only, no ANSI sequences)]' \
    && ret=0

return ret
